>>176434807
The language which seems most fun to you is what will be the best for you regardless of how useful it may be. Enjoyment is how learning languages works effectively. If they are all equal then consider which language you may be more likely to use in the future, in travel, in relationships, or even in work. If you still can’t decide then you can’t go wrong with picking a language where there are a lot of speakers worldwide or an official UN language can be quite nice. Finally, if none of the above advice was useful then I’d probably just choose which one would give me some nice bragging rights desu.

Moving out of Russia: German
Job opportunities: Chinese

Consuming media: Spanish

If they play dumb and start asking you what kind of apartment you are looking for, the ad is not genuine and you cannot trust them, they will waste your time. Only make appointments if they promise to show you the apartment from the ad. Otherwise they will take you to see shit apartments and convince you that it's a nice place to live.

posts.com:
Det jeg hader mest ved vores arbejdssamfund er hvordan vi mennesker næsten udelukkende anskues som den funktion vi har i vores rolle som skatteslaver.
Dette ses i diskurserne som "varme hænder", "lønmodtagere", "arbejdstagere", "skatteyderne". Vi er aldrig bare mennesker. Hvis vi er heldige refereres vi til som "danskerne" i bestemt flertal form. Det er en trist stadie for mennesket at vores højeste formål er at tjene staten penge så vi "kan blive rigere". Hvad endnu mere trist er, at dette er helt åbenlyst det klare mål. Bare vi bliver rigere og kan holde hjulene i gang, så har samfundet det godt. Regler bliver indført som ska sikre at vi aldrig nogensinde opnår mere frihed. Kulturen er indrettet af samme hånd sådan at vi heller aldrig stopper op mentalt og spirituelt for at søge en dybere mening, i stedet spises vi af med brød og cirkus produkter, kortvarige letfordærvelige kulturoplevelser der akkurat er tilstrækkelige til at distrahere os i den korte fritid vi nu engang alligevel har. Det klinger hult at selv samme system nu opråber om børn og unges mentale helbred som oftest kædes sammen med teknologi og sociale medier og alting går hurtigt og ironisk nok foreslår samme beaurukratiske maskine som selv ansporer til at tage del i dette rotteræs at de nu har løsningen gennem flere mærkelige psykiatriske indsatser rettet mod børn.

Måske skal vores samfund bare snart komme til den indrømmelse at det er systemet og vores levemåde, som er vores reelle sygdom frem for at symptombehandle og håbe at dulme folk nok med rosenrøde løgne, manipulation og medicinering.

Anon er træt af det og vil gerne leve et liv i harmoni og fred men samfundet gør alt for at holde kløerne fast i ham så det kan udnytte hans arbejdskraft indtil hans krop giver efter i gammel alder og samfundet ikke længere kan bruge ham til noget

>Describe/discuss your favorite meals edition

Aligot

It requires
>mashed potatoes
>cream
>butter
>"tome fraîche" cheese (a lot, like a 1/3 of the weight of all the other ingredients)
>crushed garlic
>herbs salt pepper etc

Basically you mix everything together and the goal is to really FUSE the cheese with the potatoes, you need to end up with a smooth, uniform, creamy mashed potatoes that's also elastic and cheesy as fuck. It requires to be stirred constantly and to lift the mixture into the air with your spoon to extend the cheese (pic rel)
Usually served with a large grilled sausage

"tome fraîche" is a fresh pressed cow cheese normally only produced by Aubrac and Salers breed in the highlands of southern France, but in that case it's not for the sake of being a fancy choice it's really on the very few cheeses that'll be able to achieve that smooth, silky texture
There must be substitutes out there but I don't know them. Doesn't work with mozzarella or other typically "elastic" cheeses.

I've failed to make it at home even with the proper cheese tbf, but it's widely available on menus in the Massif Central. It's specifically a recipe from the Aubrac plateau

>Les délire d'esprit comme l'animisme ça vient selon moi de ce genre de chose. L'esprit humain et ces profondeur. Après il faut avoir expérimenté avec l'esprit et non pas seulement avoir vécu bloquer dans le monde matériel et l'ego. Suffit de méditer pour comprendre
Anon, bien que chacun soit libre dans son approche du bouddhisme, l'instrumentaliser pour justifier tes croyances personnelles à l'extérieur de toi, ça sort vraiment de la philosophie bouddhique.
Je suis un novice (disons "Hinayana ") mais j'ai suivi les enseignements d'un moine, étant curieux d'en savoir plus (notamment sur les similitudes avec le Stoïcisme).

Oui, dans la culture tibétaine il y a l'idée de fantôme (l'état Bardo avant la réincarnation), mais c'est similaire à l'idée chrétienne que le corps doit être enterré intact pour la résurrection ou que le pain de la messe se transforme en corps du Christ. Ce sont des métaphores ou interprétations. Se focaliser sur cette partie de manière concrète ne mène nulle part. En plus dans l'ouest on associe souvent "Fantôme" à une silhouette blanchâtre humanoïde, mais dans ce cas c'est plus d'idée "d'esprit/énergie" dont tout est imprégné.
Mais tout ça, c'est personnel. Une façon d'interpréter le même monde que tout le monde partage. D'où le mot "croire": ce qui n'est pas vérifiable et just ressenti, ça n'existe pas en réalité... et ce n'est pas un problème du tout. Ça peut exister en toi, donc c'est "réel" pour toi, mais ça reste une croyance. Tout est possible dans ta tête ou la mienne, les croyances par définition ne peuvent pas être prouvées, donc toute croyance est possible et se vaut. Quand on se demande si quelque chose existe/est réel, on sort du monde personnel (où toute croyance est possible) et on s'en tient aux faits. Donc "tu médite pas donc tu te permet d'avoir un opinion sur qq chose d'inconnu", demander à ce que les gens respectent X protocole pour en parler, ça n'a pas de sens. Il n'y pas de débat à avoir.

rye, barley, wheat. in the form of porridge, pottage (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pottage), bread, etc. in grain and flour forms. bread was baked constantly in communal ovens (think like a bigger fire pizza oven). flour was made in mills and taxed there as payment and in stone hand grinding wheels which many homes had (you grind it as you need it, very slow output).

ale in the north and wine in the south were ubiquitous. more so than plain water. these were not aged and not the sorts that keep long. would be constantly made by a household. would be mostly low alcohol but higher alc existed.

everyone would have their own vegetable gardens for personal eating.

poultry, eggs, milk and various milk products, any animal that is too old, defective, or you can't feed (i.e. during winter when you need food and can't feed all your animals). lots of fish, preserved and fresh, seafood if you live by the sea. small game such as birds (which anyone is allowed to hunt, unlike larger game).
